'''Komo Shrine''' (こうもうじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Tatsugi, {{ill|lt=Tone|Q1203324|qid=Q1203324|1=Tone, Ibaraki}}, {{ill|lt=Kitasōma District|Q1076978|qid=Q1076978|1=Kitasōma District, Ibaraki}}, {{ill|lt=Ibaraki Prefecture|Q83273|qid=Q83273|1=Ibaraki Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha in Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, and its former rank under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=Gōsha in modern ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=gōsha|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}.

=== Overview ===
It stands in southern Ibaraki, on one part of the {{ill|lt=Inashiki Plateau|Q102282520|qid=Q102282520|1=Hitachi Plateau}}. It is slightly south between Tone town center and {{ill|lt=Ryūgasaki|Q844138|qid=Q844138|1=Ryūgasaki, Ibaraki}} city center. The {{ill|lt=Shin-Tone River|Q11501429|qid=Q11501429|1=Shin-Tone River}} flows south of the shrine grounds.

It consists of two shrine buildings, Kado-no-miya and Oku-no-miya. The current Kado-no-miya honden was rebuilt in 1698 ({{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|qid=Q1325001|1=Genroku}} 11, {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|qid=Q184963|1=Edo period}}), and the Oku-no-miya honden in 1703 (Genroku 16). The Kado-no-miya honden is a Tone Town designated cultural property<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.town.tone.ibaraki.jp/kanko-bunka/rekisibunka/shiseki-bunkazai/page000161.html|title=Tone Town official site: Komo Shrine Kado-no-miya (left) / Oku-no-miya (right) |accessdate=2025-11-08}}</ref>.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|lt=Mizuhanome|Q8191796|qid=Q8191796|lt=Mizuhanome-no-Ōkami|1=Mizuhanome}}
* {{ill|lt=Haniyasu|Q9285919|qid=Q9285919|lt=Haniyamahime-no-Ōkami|1=Haniyasu-hiko and Haniyasu-hime}}
* {{ill|lt=Kagutsuchi|Q1640658|qid=Q1640658|lt=Kagutsuchi-no-Ōkami|1=Kagu-tsuchi}}
* {{ill|lt=Kanayamahiko|Q4387856|qid=Q4387856|lt=Kanayamahiko-no-Ōkami|1=Kanayama-hiko and Kanayama-hime}}
* {{ill|qid=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama|Q3080728|qid=Q3080728|qid=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama-no-Ōkami|1=Ukanomitama}}
* {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|qid=Q272993|lt=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}}
* {{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|qid=Q382005|lt=Sugawara no Michizane-kō|1=Sugawara no Michizane}}
* {{ill|lt=Hachiman|Q261637|qid=Q261637|lt=Honda-wake-no-Ōkami|1=Hachiman}}
The main deity is Mizuhanome-no-Ōkami, a water goddess governing water as the source of life. Many other deities, including Haniyamahime-no-Ōkami, are also {{ill|lt=merged|Q11412524|qid=Q11412524|1=Co-Enshrinement}} in the paired hall.

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, it began in 288 BCE ({{ill|lt=Emperor Kōrei|Q313041|qid=Q313041|1=Emperor Kōrei}} 3) with enshrinement of Mizuhanome-no-Ōkami at the present Kado-no-miya site. Later, in 698 CE ({{ill|lt=Emperor Monmu|Q357246|qid=Q357246|1=Emperor Monmu}} 2), Haniyamahime-no-Ōkami was enshrined in the paired hall and the buildings were restored<ref name=history>{{cite web |url=http://www.koumoujinja.jp/what_koumou.html|title=Komo Shrine official site|accessdate=2025-11-08}}</ref>.

In the {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|qid=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, it was listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} as “Komo Shrine, one seat, Sōma District, {{ill|lt=Shimōsa Province|Q1053695|qid=Q1053695|1=Shimōsa Province}},” and was ranked a shikinaisha<ref name=history></ref>.

From the {{ill|lt=medieval period|Q12554|qid=Q12554|1=Middle Ages}} onward it was also called “Bumma Daimyōjin,” gathering faith as a local water deity. Since the {{ill|lt=early modern period|Q5308718|qid=Q5308718|1=Early modern period}}, it has inherited worship for rain-prayer, rain-stopping, and abundant harvest as the “oldest water-deity shrine in {{ill|lt=Kantō|Q11655841|qid=Q11655841|1=Kantō}},” and remains revered as a local guardian deity<ref name=history></ref>.

